  "why": "The paper demonstrates cross-model transferability of the generated adversarial examples. In the evaluation of defense techniques (RQ4), the authors generate 'uncommon data' on original models and then test this data against defended models (e.g., those retrained using defensive distillation or label smoothing). A defended model is a distinct, retrained version of the original, so testing inputs generated on the original against the defended one is a form of transferability analysis. The paper explicitly refers to this as a \"transfer attack scenario\" and states that the data reveals \"stronger transferability\". However, the fuzzing design itself (KuK) is guided by uncertainty metrics from a single model at a time and does not incorporate explicit mechanisms (like using surrogate models in the feedback loop) to maximize the discovery of transferable failures. This meets the criteria for 'Medium'.",
